shortDesc: Curious and friendly; a frequent visitor to feeders.
longDesc: A curious little bird that's not afraid to approach humans. Black-capped Chickadees have a black cap and bib, with a white streak running through the middle. They also have gray wings and a slightly yellowish belly.

shortDesc: A brown teal with a white moustache.
longDesc: Males are mostly brown with a black head, a white tail, and a white moustache. In fliight, you can get a glimpse of the blue patches along the wings. Females are brown, but still have a blue patch on their wings.

shortDesc: A black goose that hangs around seawater.
longDesc: The Brant has a white ring around its neck, a white patch on its wings, and a white tail. Other than that, it is mostly black. It prefers to be in costal areas in the winter. The Brant migrates to Siberia in the summer.
A mostly brown goose with a short black neck and white cheeks. It has a short, thin bill. Lives year-around and is commonly seen with people in parks, wetlands, golf courses, and ponds.

shortDesc: A goose that delights in chasing small children.
longDesc: A mostly brown goose with a long black neck and white cheeks. It has a long, thick bill. It lives year-around and is commonly seen with people in parks, wetlands, golf courses, and ponds.

shortDesc: Brown goose with an orange bill and a white forehead.
longDesc: The Greater White-fronted Goose is smaller than a Canada Goose. It's plumage is brown with an orange bill and orange legs. Sticks around for the winter and is usually found among flocks of other geese.

shortDesc: Medium-sized white goose with red bill.
longDesc: The Snow Goose has two different plumages, a white morph and blue morph. The white morph, which is usually found in Washington, is completely white with a red bill and a black tail. The blue morph has a white head, and is primarly black. Snow geese stay the winter in Washington, arriving in early October and leaving in April.

shortDesc: If this bird was an albino, you would never know.
longDesc: The trumpeter swan is the largest waterfowl in North America. Completely white with a black bill. It's call sounds like “oh-OH”, with the second "OH" being more prominant. This swan sticks around during the winter.

shortDesc: Lives in wooded wetlands, but terrible at camouflage.
longDesc: This duck is a whistlling duck. Males during breeding season have a green crest, a red eye, a white chin, brown chest, yellow belly, and black-and-blue wings. Females are overall brown with white dots on chest, a white chin, and a white ring around its eye. Nonbreeding males are mostly brown with red eyes.
